ould reduce efforts. Lack of appropriate expertise may also be an issue.   The effectiveness of partnering of Academies to raise standards may be limited by the competition between schools and other form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s of dissemination of best practice may help a larger number of schools.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a need for local management and co-ordination that should be provided by local authorities.  Local Authorities should set admissions policies, rather than academies, as th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ey must ensure policies across an area are compatible. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Local authorities should also have a role in a regional governance layer between academies and the DfE.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy chains </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> improve cooperation within the chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this is likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at the expens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e of wider cooperation.   Chains may be attractive due to their ability to share resources, but the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accountability to parents and visibility of their finances.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is particularly important given the instances of finan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cial mismangement in acad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They also may change the financial landscape tipping the balance in favour of academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the expense of parental choice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It would appear prudent to limit the dominance of any particular academy chain in an area as this will have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an impact on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parental choice. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There appears to be little evidence that academisation is beneficial schools and in the context of the recent failures of governance at free schools and academies, the financial overspends and the problems experienced with the Swedish fr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ee school program then the conversion of primary schools to academies seems to involve high risks for questionable gain.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some of the issues on which views were sought are addressed in more detail below. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">”</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academisation was expected to narrow the gap in two ways.  Schools were expected to benefi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t directly through sponsorship when they became academies, but also t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">op performing academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are expected to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">performing schools to raise standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the nature of the assistance from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">top performing schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is not clear and this may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suffer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> due to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conflicting interests.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An example is that of Tudor Grange Academy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, an Outstanding school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Solihull</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Solihull LEA has several </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">secondary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools in the N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">orth of the borough rated as either as Inadequate or Satisfactory / Requires improvem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent.   In 2013 Tudor Grange </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changed its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> admissions policy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">St James</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Primary school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adopted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tudor Grange </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a week before, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">became a feeder school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Parents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were angered that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">displace</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">while giving highest priority t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o those living further away. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">referred to its narrowing the gap agenda as a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> justification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> because</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">St James was situated i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n a small area </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relative deprivation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> surrounded by more affluent regions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Parents argued that a change in admissions policy wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in itself</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> improve standards at the primary school but that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">real </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improvements w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould result from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sharing of knowledge and expertise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which could take place regardless of admissions policy.   It was also seen that while the primary school was set in an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> area of relative deprivation, the children in that area went on to gain KS4 results that were above the national average due to attending other good secondary schools in the area.  No answer was given as to why the school felt it appropriate to focus on c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren that are already above the national average while ignoring those schools with far worse results.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> other secondary schools in the area would bring benefits to a large number of children, whereas the link with St James merely benefits a sm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all number of children at the expense of others.    This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> raises questions about how schools work together to narrow the gap.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should high performing schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">select </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the schools with which t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hey will work to narrow the gap?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It appears that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are not required to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be aimed where there is the greatest need or where they will have greatest impact.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">igh performing schools can simply select schools they are disposed towards while avoiding the schools with the greatest needs and challen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ges.    The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tudor Grange </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">example also show</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the potential for conflicting interests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that are part of a chain will naturally focus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their attentions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on their own schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and potentially expanding into other areas, such as setting up their own se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rvice companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This leaves little </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">time and resources available for narrowing the gap outside the Academy chain.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is not clear whether high performing Academies can simply avoid requests for assistance or take other actions to deliberately avoid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working with certain schools.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Several questions were asked about the Schools policy and actions in relation to narrowing the gap but no answers were given. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ( This is somewhat typical of the Academy which has not answered many of the questions asked by p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arents, who have little recourse via the DFE.) </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What should actually be done</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to narrow the gap?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As discussed previously there are some actions that merely play lip-service to narrowing the gap rather than having a material impact.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Useful partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are likely to involve sharing experience and resources. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sharing experience</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.83pt; padding-left:6.17pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There’s some doubt as to whether top performing academies actually have the skills necessary to help.  For example, an academy set in a leafy suburb serving highly aspirational ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ildren may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not be able to advise on how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to improve an inner city school serving disengaged children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uch advice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">might</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be better sought from another inner city school that had managed to improve standards, regardless of whether they were an academy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Si</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">milarly one of the key features in improving standards is being able to engage with parents and work in partnership with them.   This is not necessarily something that Academies excel at and could be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">case of the blind leading the blind. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The division be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tween Academies and other schools is somewhat artificial and may prevent wider improvement. For example if academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">perform better due to being able to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allocate resources more effectively than LEA maintained schools, should this not feed back into the way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> LEA budgets are managed? It is unclear why partnering schools together is a better mechanism for improvement than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> studying those schools that have undergone positive transformation and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sharing the lessons learned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The goal must be to determine what is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effective in raising standards and what is not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to disseminate this widely.  It may be argued that strategies may prove to be successful in some situations and not others, but that would also be the case for partnering schools together. </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sharing resour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ces</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are already mechanisms to share resources such as the teachers resource exchange used for presentations and teaching applications. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The loaning of equipment from one school to another may be effective where equipment is not needed all year round.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Again, it is easy to see how first preference would be to schools within the same academy chai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n. Where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resources could be shared then it may be better for the LEA to manage a resource library on behalf of all the schools in the area, giving preferential a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccess to the schools with greatest need.  Where resources are in situ then these can only be shared by o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pening school premises for use by other schools.  While this should be encouraged, there may well be practical issues around when resources can be made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">available and the distance between schools.  In Solihull three schools are located on the same site yet there appears to be no sharing of resources between them. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One new area of potential assistance is where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">run service companies. Tudor Grange o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffers services for IT, catering, adminstration and financial services and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be compelled to offer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these services to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the areas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">underperforming schools at cost. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Again, the forces that put schools in competition with each other may not result in maximisi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng co-operation.</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level."</span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local authorities should set admissions policies for all schools in their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> area.  Where Academies set their own policies this can result in policies that are not com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">patible with each other. Local A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uthorities are also less likely than Academies to try and game the admissions policy of any particular school for its own advantage. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Authorities co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld have a valuable co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ordinating role for addressing how schools can work together to narrow the gap.  While Local Authorities can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’t have sole ultimate control over Free Schools or A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cademies, they should have a role in resolving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and should definitely have a role in a governance layer between the free schools/academies and the DfE due to their knowledge of local issues and priorities. The proposed members of the chancellor boards would all have their own agendas, so to assert that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> excluding local authorities will keep them free of local politics is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, at best, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">optimistic.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy chains allow for shared resources and policies between schools in that chain.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It may be that geographically based LEAs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increasingly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> replaced by sponsor based groupings.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> With a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> diminishing number of schools to manage, the fixed overheads of LEAs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may result in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">poor value for money</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where LEAs were previously efficient. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   In the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">case of Tudor Grange, the creation of an academy chain resulted in a reduction in the overall leadership team and a streamlining of the governance structure such that it is hard for parents to have a say in the running of their school.  Parents of existing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools within the chain have no say in the adoption of other schools, though this diverts the leadership team from managing the existing schools.  Academy chains can become, like the banks, “too big to fail”.  If a large </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chain went into administr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation it is hard to see what other provider could step into the breach.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This increases the uncertainty for parents while the benefits of chain membership are unclear.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors ap</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ply;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;</span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There appears to be no evidence that academisation is the key to improving results, with improvement being s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">imilar among maintained schools and academies.  There seem to have been efforts to present the data selectively to show</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an advantage.  Some of the issues are explained in more detail at http://www.localschoolsnetwork.org.uk/2013/05/the-academies-illusion-w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat-the-data-reveals/</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 34.4pt; padding-left:1.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is cer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tainly counter intuitive that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools will improve by employing untrained teachers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Similarly there seems to be little point in developing a national curriculum that is on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly mandatory for some schools.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Primary schools may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> simply lack the scale to have sufficient resources to operate independently of the LEA.  Some LEAs are better than others at improving standards and it would seem that co-operation between effective and ineffective LEAs would be more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">useful than academy c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onversion. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onverting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primary schools to academies appears to be a strategy that is high risk, reduces accountability and has dubious benefits.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>